This paper deals with the security and game-theoretic analysis of the Bitcoin protocol, which involves cryptography (cs.CR), distributed computing (cs.DC), game theory (cs.GT), network infrastructure (cs.NI), and social networks (cs.SI). The focus on the behavior of multiple selfish miners suggests that cs.CR and cs.GT are the most likely categories, followed by cs.DC and cs.NI, which deal with the technical aspects of the Bitcoin protocol. The mention of social networks in the abstract suggests that cs.SI may also be relevant, although to a lesser extent.
